WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.360
My name is Eduardo Arrino de la Rubia, and I am fortunate enough to be the moderator

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:18.040
for your panel this afternoon, evening, I don't know what time zone I'm in, to be honest

00:00:18.040 --> 00:00:19.559
with you.

00:00:19.559 --> 00:00:25.520
The goal of our panel is to provide you, the audience, our dear friends, with an understanding

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:29.680
of how the data science leaders who have been kind enough to share their time with us today

00:00:29.680 --> 00:00:34.680
think about growth and change in careers, organizations, and responsibility in data

00:00:34.680 --> 00:00:38.160
science, and we're very lucky to have them.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:42.639
For just a little bit about me, I have been involved in data science since before it had

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:48.080
a cool name like data science, I've been fortunate enough to hire my first machine learning engineer

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:53.000
in the late 90s, and ever since then I've had the incredible fortune of just supporting

00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:57.119
great teams, I'm currently a data science leader at Instagram.

00:00:57.119 --> 00:01:01.360
And so now I will be introducing the panel to you.

00:01:01.360 --> 00:01:04.720
Immediately to my left is Angela.

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:09.519
For the past 15 years, she has helped make businesses intelligently use data to make

00:01:09.519 --> 00:01:12.139
decisions and trained others to do so.

00:01:12.139 --> 00:01:15.760
And she likes to see the impact of her work making a difference every day.

00:01:15.760 --> 00:01:18.980
Her thoughts on data science management have been published in the Harvard Business Review

00:01:18.980 --> 00:01:22.839
and the Wall Street Journal, and her projects as an individual contributor have gone on

00:01:22.839 --> 00:01:28.000
to earn accolades such as Inform's Edelman Award for Achievement in Operations Research,

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:32.160
and the Management Sciences and the Massachusetts Innovation and Technology Exchange Award for

00:01:32.160 --> 00:01:34.379
Big Data and Analytics Innovations.

00:01:34.379 --> 00:01:37.820
She finds passion in the craft and she is consistently seeking improvements and better

00:01:37.820 --> 00:01:39.320
ways to solve tough problems.

00:01:39.320 --> 00:01:47.400
So everybody say hello to Angela.

00:01:47.400 --> 00:01:52.199
Next we have Hilary Parker, she is a data scientist on the styling recommendations team

00:01:52.559 --> 00:01:53.559
at Stitch Fix.

00:01:53.559 --> 00:01:58.040
At Stitch Fix, she focuses on what sorts of data to collect from clients in order to optimize

00:01:58.040 --> 00:02:02.680
clothing recommendations, as well as building out prototypes of algorithms or entirely new

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:05.519
products based on new data sources.

00:02:05.519 --> 00:02:09.800
You also might know her as the co-founder of the Not So Standard Deviations podcast,

00:02:09.800 --> 00:02:11.740
which she does with Roger Peng.

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:16.440
It's a bi-weekly data science podcast that now has over half a million downloads.

00:02:16.479 --> 00:02:23.880
So everybody say hello to Hilary.

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:25.399
Next we have Karthik.

00:02:25.399 --> 00:02:29.679
So Karthik Ram is a research scientist at the Berkeley Institute for Data Science and

00:02:29.679 --> 00:02:35.199
the University of California Museum of Paleontology at University of California Berkeley.

00:02:35.199 --> 00:02:39.440
Karthik is also the co-founder of the R Open Sci Project, lead of the U.S. Research Software

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:44.600
Sustainability Institute, founding editor at the Journal of Open Source Software, and

00:02:44.600 --> 00:02:49.000
has served on the boards of various organizations in this space, including Data Carpentry, Many

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:51.440
Labs, Libraries.io, and more.

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:58.160
So everybody say hello to Karthik.

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:02.360
And finally, way down at the end right there, we have Dr. Tracy Thiel.

00:03:02.360 --> 00:03:07.759
Dr. Thiel is a co-founder of Data Carpentry and now the executive director of the Carpentries.

00:03:07.759 --> 00:03:11.119
She received her PhD in computational and neural systems from the California Institute

00:03:11.119 --> 00:03:16.520
of Technology, was an NSF postdoctoral researcher in biological informatics, then an assistant

00:03:16.520 --> 00:03:20.119
professor in microbiology at Michigan State University.

00:03:20.119 --> 00:03:23.800
While an associate professor, she saw a researcher's need for effective data skills to effectively

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:28.639
and reproducibly conduct research and co-founded Data Carpentry to scale data training along

00:03:28.639 --> 00:03:30.520
with data production.

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:36.339
She's involved in the open source software, I didn't write that right, and reproducible

00:03:36.339 --> 00:03:41.220
research communities, including as an editor at the Journal for Open Source Software and

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:42.820
the Journal for Open Source Education.

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:51.460
So everybody say hello to Dr. Tracy Thiel.

00:03:51.460 --> 00:03:56.100
So when I agreed to do this panel, I was shocked at the breadth that I was allowed to have.

00:03:56.100 --> 00:04:00.220
I really was not given any constraints on what to talk about.

00:04:00.220 --> 00:04:03.860
And that's both really freeing and a little terrifying.

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:08.300
And I thought actually back to the previous panel that I was on at this conference, and

00:04:08.300 --> 00:04:13.860
I remembered that we had so many questions from folks about how to grow in data science.

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:16.859
You know, people like I want to get into data science, I'm a junior analyst, I want to become

00:04:16.859 --> 00:04:21.459
a data scientist, people asking about organizations, and I decided let's just do a panel entirely

00:04:21.459 --> 00:04:22.459
on growth.

00:04:22.459 --> 00:04:24.940
So I'm going to kick it off with my first question.

00:04:24.940 --> 00:04:26.899
And so this is to the panel.

00:04:26.899 --> 00:04:29.940
The career path in data science is different for all of us.

00:04:29.940 --> 00:04:33.660
What is the most important lesson you've learned about growing as a data scientist, whether

00:04:33.660 --> 00:04:38.140
it be your personal growth experience or how you've fostered growth in others?

00:04:38.140 --> 00:04:41.980
Does anyone want to take it to start?

00:04:41.980 --> 00:04:44.299
I can start.

00:04:44.299 --> 00:04:50.820
So yeah, I mean, I think you're totally right that careers in data science, I think we finally

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:53.339
hired someone who had a master's in data science recently.

00:04:53.339 --> 00:04:58.660
So out of 120 people in the data science or get stitch fix, there's one person who was

00:04:58.660 --> 00:05:02.619
like formally trained in data science.

00:05:02.619 --> 00:05:09.459
And so I think that some of the most important things from my perspective are being really

00:05:09.459 --> 00:05:12.179
nimble with the tools that you're learning.

00:05:12.179 --> 00:05:18.899
I think that keeping like being very flexible with tooling is super important, because in

00:05:18.899 --> 00:05:24.140
the various different jobs, you're going to be tackling different problems.

00:05:24.140 --> 00:05:31.179
And there's really no space for being a purist in terms of like, the most important thing

00:05:31.179 --> 00:05:33.700
is being able to get a job done.

00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:39.500
And so being a purist with your tooling and trying to get every problem into a very specific

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:42.459
format just isn't going to happen.

00:05:42.459 --> 00:05:48.420
At Stitch Fix specifically, we have this philosophy of kind of a full stack data scientist, which

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.380
is like obviously has pros and cons.

00:05:51.380 --> 00:05:56.820
But one of the big pros is that you end up having to create like scrappy solutions for

00:05:56.820 --> 00:05:57.820
almost everything.

00:05:57.820 --> 00:06:04.339
So like learning how to create ETL from web blogs all the way to like front end applications.

00:06:04.339 --> 00:06:08.540
So yeah, just like kind of having like a growth mindset and being really flexible is super

00:06:08.540 --> 00:06:09.540
important.

00:06:09.540 --> 00:06:14.700
And then the other thing I'll say is that I actually think some of the more, I mean,

00:06:14.700 --> 00:06:18.220
I hate this term, but kind of like the softer skills are super important.

00:06:18.220 --> 00:06:24.019
So like, especially like cultivating empathy, I think is really important for the job and

00:06:24.019 --> 00:06:27.100
something that we don't talk about very much.

00:06:27.380 --> 00:06:31.619
But understanding users, understanding the people who are reading the analyses you're

00:06:31.619 --> 00:06:35.779
putting out there, I mean, that's in some ways the most important part because you can

00:06:35.779 --> 00:06:40.899
do a perfect data analysis, but if you're, you know, speaking a different language than

00:06:40.899 --> 00:06:44.820
the person who's consuming it, you might as well have not done it.

00:06:44.820 --> 00:06:52.420
And so I think that's kind of an unsung hero of successful data science work.

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:53.420
So yeah.

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:54.420
Yeah.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:56.440
A question for you about that.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:01.679
So I like that you were talking about not being a purist.

00:07:01.679 --> 00:07:06.760
How do you balance then, or what advice do you give for folks balancing actually creating

00:07:06.760 --> 00:07:11.760
breadth in the technologies they know with actually having enough depth in any one thing?

00:07:11.760 --> 00:07:13.760
And this can be you or anyone on the panel.

00:07:13.760 --> 00:07:14.760
Yeah.

00:07:14.760 --> 00:07:18.760
I'm not sure I have a great, I don't know if I have a great answer to that, but I mean,

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:23.679
certainly I'm obviously, I mean, for people who know me, I'm like obviously really into

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:24.679
R.

00:07:24.679 --> 00:07:30.239
So I think that learning one language really fluently, I know that's advice that Hadley

00:07:30.239 --> 00:07:34.279
Wickham gives of like kind of like a depth in one language is very powerful.

00:07:34.279 --> 00:07:38.279
And I think, I think a lot of the general concepts from one language to another translate

00:07:38.279 --> 00:07:39.279
really well.

00:07:39.279 --> 00:07:44.000
So I found it really effective to get a lot of depth in one language and kind of a deep

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.519
understanding of like the work I'm doing through that.

00:07:47.519 --> 00:07:51.440
And then being willing to be flexible and work in these other languages, like, you know,

00:07:51.440 --> 00:07:54.600
we probably all write SQL queries and we don't talk about it very much.

00:07:54.640 --> 00:07:55.640
I'm guessing.

00:07:55.640 --> 00:07:56.640
Yeah.

00:07:56.640 --> 00:07:57.640
Or I know I do.

00:07:57.640 --> 00:07:59.640
So, you know, there's a lot of concepts.

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:03.880
I mean, I learned SQL best by learning dplyr and then being able to translate over.

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.279
So yeah, that's my answer.

00:08:06.279 --> 00:08:10.679
Angela, you know, I know you've managed data science teams, you've had junior data scientists.

00:08:10.679 --> 00:08:15.440
What advice do you give to junior data scientists who want to grow in their career?

00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:24.040
I think I have extreme respect for junior data scientists, especially because being

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:31.880
in the sexiest profession of the 21st century, yes, thank you for laughing, yes.

00:08:31.880 --> 00:08:38.739
I think it made sense when, when DJ Patil wrote the article to have that articulation

00:08:38.739 --> 00:08:39.739
of the profession.

00:08:39.739 --> 00:08:44.599
But I think it's created a sense that it's really difficult to break into unless you

00:08:44.760 --> 00:08:49.799
have a PhD, unless you have two PhDs, unless you have two PhDs and a body of work and three

00:08:49.799 --> 00:08:53.460
published books and a collaboration with a Nobel laureate.

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:55.280
And that's not true.

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:57.440
I don't have a PhD.

00:08:57.440 --> 00:09:01.599
And you stole my joke, but I've been doing data science before it had a cool name or

00:09:01.599 --> 00:09:04.200
before I had heard of said cool name.

00:09:04.200 --> 00:09:08.799
And so I think, and I, and I harp on this a lot.

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:13.559
I think being a junior data scientist is a gift.

00:09:14.020 --> 00:09:16.640
It's a gift that you bring to any organization.

00:09:16.640 --> 00:09:23.200
And if you feel that joining an organization is too difficult because they're giving you

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:25.919
a hard time because of how junior you are.

00:09:25.919 --> 00:09:29.799
I know not everybody has this privilege, but I would make you consider strongly whether

00:09:29.799 --> 00:09:33.119
or not you actually do want to join that organization.

00:09:33.119 --> 00:09:38.900
Because what you bring is you bring the ability to question dogma.

00:09:38.900 --> 00:09:45.140
Because you ideally, by virtue of your tenure in the discipline, haven't been indoctrinated

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:46.859
yet into the dogma.

00:09:46.859 --> 00:09:53.239
And so you bring a breadth of ignorance.

00:09:53.239 --> 00:09:55.940
And I say that in the best possible way.

00:09:55.940 --> 00:09:59.340
You don't know what's supposed to be done a certain way.

00:09:59.340 --> 00:10:03.619
You don't know what isn't allowed to be questioned anymore.

00:10:03.619 --> 00:10:10.219
And I think that's something that can be extremely useful for, for any organization.

00:10:10.219 --> 00:10:14.140
And so I think that's not something to hide or to shy away from.

00:10:14.140 --> 00:10:19.340
I think the ability to be vulnerable and the ability to say I don't know are actually extremely

00:10:19.340 --> 00:10:21.260
valuable to me as a hiring manager.

00:10:21.260 --> 00:10:29.159
I actually have in my interviewing guide questions that are impossible to be answered.

00:10:29.159 --> 00:10:33.599
Or at least impossible to be answered succinctly in the time allotted.

00:10:33.599 --> 00:10:39.520
And that's because the thing that I'm testing is whether you have the humility to say I

00:10:39.520 --> 00:10:40.520
don't know.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:43.760
And whether you have the hubris to say but I can figure it out.

00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:50.919
And that's the balance that I think is, is the balance that I would recommend younger

00:10:50.919 --> 00:10:54.099
folks in the discipline to try to strike.

00:10:54.099 --> 00:10:58.760
One of my favorite data science executives was pushing back that his team only wanted

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:00.239
to hire senior data scientists.

00:11:00.960 --> 00:11:03.760
And he was like, you really need to stop doing that.

00:11:03.760 --> 00:11:05.359
Junior data scientists are better.

00:11:05.359 --> 00:11:08.080
They don't know what is impossible yet.

00:11:08.080 --> 00:11:10.080
And I really, that strikes me.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:12.640
The one thing that I'll add, I think these are all great answers.

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:15.200
What do y'all think about ruthless prioritization?

00:11:15.200 --> 00:11:19.679
I think that as a junior data scientist, junior data scientists oftentimes in product teams

00:11:19.679 --> 00:11:24.840
are sort of like the target of product managers, of engineering managers.

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:27.359
And they're thrashed in every which way.

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:30.159
Do you have any great advice that you give junior data scientists?

00:11:30.159 --> 00:11:33.880
On how to own their communication style or ruthless prioritization?

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:34.880
Anyone?

00:11:34.880 --> 00:11:35.880
No?

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:38.880
I'll take a stab.

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:46.479
Yeah, I really care about this question because I think that so frequently as data scientists

00:11:46.479 --> 00:11:51.239
we're in these really reactive positions, especially as like a data analyst for a product

00:11:51.239 --> 00:11:55.359
team, especially if you're probably embedded on the product team.

00:11:55.359 --> 00:12:00.039
And I know like we talk a lot about kind of building tools to enable product managers

00:12:00.039 --> 00:12:01.039
and all of that.

00:12:01.039 --> 00:12:02.039
And I think that's important.

00:12:02.039 --> 00:12:10.479
But I also think that as a data scientist, you end up thinking about the holistic product

00:12:10.479 --> 00:12:11.840
in unique ways.

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:16.840
And I actually think that another way to solve that problem is to take on some of the responsibilities

00:12:16.840 --> 00:12:19.799
that a PM might traditionally take on.

00:12:19.799 --> 00:12:25.119
Like in many ways, I think that by thinking holistically about that system, by thinking

00:12:25.119 --> 00:12:29.719
holistically about the product, you can really guide decision making.

00:12:29.719 --> 00:12:34.760
And so, I mean, to your point about ruthless prioritization, I think that by taking a more

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:40.960
proactive like non-defensive stance about really solving problems can put you into a

00:12:40.960 --> 00:12:45.400
place where you're really a genuine partner with a product manager rather than just kind

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:49.000
of like they're the person who crunches numbers for them.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:52.679
And obviously, that's something like as you get more senior, that gets easier and easier

00:12:52.679 --> 00:12:53.679
to do.

00:12:53.679 --> 00:12:58.039
But that's one of the things I really love about my job right now is that I've built

00:12:58.039 --> 00:13:03.000
some really good relationships with product managers where I don't feel like I'm kind

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.840
of just doing requests for them.

00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:09.400
I really feel like I'm guiding the product development.

00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:14.599
And if I could add to that, I think one of the really important things that a data scientist

00:13:14.599 --> 00:13:21.960
can do, one of the biggest sources of value is the translational step, is the ability

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:27.960
to articulate a business problem into a quantitative answerable hypothesis and then testing that

00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:29.119
and iterating.

00:13:29.119 --> 00:13:37.320
And so, going back to your point about ruthless prioritization, the ability to define that

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:43.400
prioritization, to understand what is being asked and not perform a task but perform a

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:49.000
service, to understand what is the question, formulating a path to answer.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:54.080
And if that path is not appropriate, having that dialogue with the product management,

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:59.599
with senior management, with whomever it is that is posing the business question or the

00:13:59.599 --> 00:14:07.960
academic question and working that muscle of that translational muscle, I think that

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:10.919
leads to better prioritization.

00:14:10.919 --> 00:14:15.559
And also, to be part of the dialogue of, that's fine, you have these ten follow-ups,

00:14:15.559 --> 00:14:17.799
what doesn't get done?

00:14:17.799 --> 00:14:19.559
Because time isn't infinite.

00:14:19.559 --> 00:14:26.679
And bringing that context in, I think, is how I guide the more junior folks on my team

00:14:26.679 --> 00:14:28.679
to react to that.

00:14:28.679 --> 00:14:32.679
So, I'm going to move on to the next question, if that's all right.

00:14:32.679 --> 00:14:37.760
So, data science organizations, whether it be a small team or a large multinational,

00:14:37.760 --> 00:14:38.760
requires data science leaders.

00:14:38.760 --> 00:14:39.760
It's just a thing.

00:14:39.760 --> 00:14:45.239
How do you think about how you choose to either become a lead yourself or how leadership is

00:14:45.239 --> 00:14:50.799
different from IC work or how we can do better to support leadership amongst our ranks?

00:14:50.799 --> 00:14:51.799
Tracy?

00:14:51.799 --> 00:14:57.719
Well, so, I really appreciate the question around leadership because that's definitely

00:14:57.719 --> 00:15:01.840
one of my soapboxes, I have quite a few.

00:15:01.840 --> 00:15:07.119
But I think that there is really, like the talk this morning, where we know things about

00:15:07.119 --> 00:15:11.799
education and we should apply the things that we know about education when we think

00:15:11.799 --> 00:15:14.039
about teaching people about programming.

00:15:14.039 --> 00:15:19.640
We know things about leadership, about what makes effective leaders, that value people

00:15:19.640 --> 00:15:26.119
and create better products, better organization, that we have an opportunity to apply in the

00:15:26.119 --> 00:15:28.440
data science space.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:33.880
But that we're not given opportunities to learn these skills, we're not necessarily

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:37.320
given opportunities to grow these skills.

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:46.960
And so, it is a real space where if we invest in thinking about leadership more strategically,

00:15:46.960 --> 00:15:51.400
more implicitly, that we can grow better leaders in data science.

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:59.719
And I think so many people have the potential to be leaders that are doing it in small ways.

00:15:59.719 --> 00:16:02.880
You don't need to lead an organization to be a leader.

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:06.039
If you're mentoring another person, you're a leader.

00:16:06.039 --> 00:16:09.359
If you're working on a small team, you're a leader.

00:16:09.359 --> 00:16:13.880
So more people seeing themselves as leaders and approaching it in a way that values the

00:16:13.880 --> 00:16:19.479
people that they work with, I would love to see more of that and I think that investing

00:16:19.479 --> 00:16:25.080
in that would be really transformational in the data science space.

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:29.440
If you could go one click more specific, what would that investment look like?

00:16:30.239 --> 00:16:36.479
Well, my secret project is that I'm not working on, but I would love to do.

00:16:36.479 --> 00:16:39.719
So as the Carpentries, our model is two-day workshops.

00:16:39.719 --> 00:16:44.359
I would love there to be something like a leadership carpentry, which is kind of a two-day

00:16:44.359 --> 00:16:48.119
thing about, I was talking to Hilary before, you know, what are the things that people

00:16:48.119 --> 00:16:56.440
don't know coming in about project management, about how to support people, how to be a mentor,

00:16:56.440 --> 00:17:01.840
interactive listening, facilitating a meeting, all like super exciting topics.

00:17:01.840 --> 00:17:02.840
These are so fun.

00:17:02.840 --> 00:17:11.520
I love all these things, but the impact of doing these things well scales so significantly

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:14.959
that it's just one of those things that I think if we invested in would have such broad

00:17:14.959 --> 00:17:15.959
impacts.

00:17:15.959 --> 00:17:18.000
So, you know, not everyone.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:20.640
Everyone should be able to take a leadership carpentry.

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:25.599
But also just understanding, I think, an appreciation that you are a leader and invest

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:29.560
in and learning more about that, looking to people who you see leading in a way that you

00:17:29.560 --> 00:17:32.079
want to lead, talking to them about that.

00:17:32.079 --> 00:17:33.319
How did they get there?

00:17:33.319 --> 00:17:34.319
What's their philosophy?

00:17:34.319 --> 00:17:40.920
What do they think about being more intentional in how we approach it and think about it?

00:17:40.920 --> 00:17:41.920
Yeah.

00:17:41.920 --> 00:17:46.280
Karthik, what do you think about the difference between leadership and IC work?

00:17:46.280 --> 00:17:48.920
This is like a challenge that I struggle with all the time.

00:17:48.920 --> 00:17:58.040
So I have a very nontraditional path into being a data scientist or sort of a data science

00:17:58.040 --> 00:17:59.119
organization leader.

00:17:59.119 --> 00:18:02.280
And so for me, I was trained as like a traditional academic.

00:18:02.280 --> 00:18:10.319
And so trying to manage a team and doing stuff to enable other people to produce data science

00:18:10.319 --> 00:18:13.880
work is not something that I'm trained to do.

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:17.920
And so Tracy and I have all these conversations about, Jesus, I'm a terrible manager.

00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:20.319
How can I be better at this thing?

00:18:20.319 --> 00:18:25.760
And we have, not just me and Tracy, but a handful of others talk about, how do we be

00:18:25.760 --> 00:18:26.760
better managers?

00:18:26.760 --> 00:18:30.800
And so this is like a constant and ongoing struggle.

00:18:30.800 --> 00:18:35.479
But I think Tracy makes an excellent point that a lot of people have potential to be

00:18:35.479 --> 00:18:41.119
leaders and trying to identify people and empower them is something critical.

00:18:41.119 --> 00:18:43.719
So I'm just figuring things out as I go.

00:18:43.719 --> 00:18:46.439
I don't quite know what I'm really doing.

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:49.400
But it looks sometimes like I know what I'm doing.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:53.560
But at least with some of these projects, one of the things I think about is, how do

00:18:53.560 --> 00:18:56.000
you get more diverse people in the room?

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.359
And then you actually find people that are leaders and then you just give them more responsibility

00:19:00.359 --> 00:19:02.199
and then they thrive.

00:19:02.199 --> 00:19:07.319
And then you sort of recognize people and we just need to do a better job of that.

00:19:07.319 --> 00:19:14.760
I think following on what Feline said this morning, that, wow, people know how to teach

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:18.199
children and we're just stumbling.

00:19:18.199 --> 00:19:21.079
I think the same thing applies to leadership and management.

00:19:21.079 --> 00:19:27.160
I think if we were more intentional, because it is a discipline unto itself and it is different.

00:19:27.160 --> 00:19:35.119
And so a little anecdote, when I first became somebody who is responsible for somebody else's

00:19:35.119 --> 00:19:40.680
ability to pay their bills, which is how I like to think about it, it's a huge responsibility.

00:19:40.680 --> 00:19:46.040
It's a huge weight on my shoulders to make sure that the people that are actually individually

00:19:46.040 --> 00:19:50.920
contributing are empowered, because I'm not.

00:19:50.920 --> 00:19:56.599
My job is to multiply their contribution.

00:19:56.599 --> 00:20:02.119
And so when I had been doing the work, I had been mentoring, I had been project managing

00:20:02.119 --> 00:20:04.760
all of that without the label.

00:20:04.760 --> 00:20:10.119
And the person who was my supervisor at the time said, you know, we want to make you the

00:20:10.119 --> 00:20:11.719
official team lead.

00:20:11.719 --> 00:20:14.920
And I went home and I cried.

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:20.359
And I called up my then boyfriend, my now husband, and I'm on the phone in tears saying,

00:20:20.359 --> 00:20:22.520
I don't want to do this.

00:20:22.520 --> 00:20:30.920
I want to be in the trenches, but it's going to be such a bad thing to bow out, to say,

00:20:30.920 --> 00:20:37.319
no, thank you, I appreciate the vote of confidence, but no, I'm going to go back to the computer.

00:20:37.400 --> 00:20:39.160
In hindsight, I love it.

00:20:39.959 --> 00:20:41.079
I absolutely love it.

00:20:41.079 --> 00:20:48.680
And so just to build on, I don't think that everybody wants to be a leader, but in my

00:20:48.680 --> 00:20:50.359
gut, no, everybody can be.

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:53.079
It's not a special skill set.

00:20:53.079 --> 00:20:58.599
It's not something that some people are gifted with genetically, the ability to do.

00:20:58.599 --> 00:21:06.520
No, I think it is a skill that is learnable, and it's about whether or not you derive the

00:21:06.520 --> 00:21:09.000
feeling of accomplishment from it.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.000
And if you do great, rock it.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:12.359
And if you don't, that's fine, too.

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:18.040
But it isn't just if you are a great individual contributor, you're naturally going to be

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:19.560
a great leader.

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:26.439
No, they're different skill sets, and they're both things that anyone with drive can learn.

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:34.680
And personally, now, years later, I look back, and I love what I do today even more, because

00:21:35.319 --> 00:21:40.839
the way that I think about it is I'm programming these folks, because you can only pay somebody

00:21:40.839 --> 00:21:42.040
to keep a seat warm.

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:46.199
You can't pay somebody to want to solve a problem in the best possible way.

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:49.959
That takes mentorship.

00:21:49.959 --> 00:21:51.479
That takes providing ability.

00:21:51.479 --> 00:21:53.319
That takes providing opportunities.

00:21:53.319 --> 00:21:58.599
That takes all sorts of things that are learnable and that are incredibly empowering, because

00:21:58.599 --> 00:22:05.719
you see the work, you see people grow, and you see people reach success because of ways

00:22:05.719 --> 00:22:09.160
that you've cleared the midfield, and you've allowed them to run their play.

00:22:11.160 --> 00:22:16.280
Oh, I would just love to add, I mean, I totally agree with everyone's talking, and I think

00:22:16.280 --> 00:22:23.319
we are in a field that kind of lionizes IC work and makes it, I think that, yeah, we

00:22:23.319 --> 00:22:27.160
sort of self-deprecate about management, where it's like, oh, I used to be an IC worker,

00:22:27.160 --> 00:22:34.280
and now I just, like, answer emails or schedule meetings, and I think that's, like, it's reflective

00:22:34.280 --> 00:22:38.839
of the fact that I think a lot of people, myself included, in this field, you're sort

00:22:38.839 --> 00:22:44.920
of, you likely came from a place where, like, your kind of personal intelligence, personal

00:22:44.920 --> 00:22:50.839
productivity was, like, you know, your self-worth, and I think that it actually takes a tremendous

00:22:50.839 --> 00:22:56.280
amount of personal work to kind of break free of that and feel like, you know, there's more

00:22:56.359 --> 00:23:02.760
to my value than, like, being the smartest person in a meeting, and there's more to success

00:23:02.760 --> 00:23:10.280
in this job than being, like, you know, the most productive coder, and so I think, I think

00:23:10.280 --> 00:23:15.800
in some other fields, that is, like, more of an understanding than in technical roles,

00:23:16.839 --> 00:23:23.160
and so I think that, like, investing in kind of your personal identity work, for lack of

00:23:23.160 --> 00:23:28.119
a better term, and, like, kind of feeling settled inside helps to kind of understand,

00:23:28.119 --> 00:23:34.359
like, these multidimensional facets of being an effective leader, and so, again, I feel

00:23:34.359 --> 00:23:38.599
like that was kind of a personal journey for me, going from kind of an academic setting,

00:23:38.599 --> 00:23:44.439
where, like, there's kind of one thing, and it's being smart, into, like, this role where,

00:23:44.439 --> 00:23:49.800
like, partnership's so important, leadership, like, just, it's just, like, a more complete,

00:23:50.599 --> 00:23:53.000
I don't know, intersection with the world.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:23:58.520
I'm kind of, I'm ecstatic that you talked about that. Whenever I talk to folks about

00:23:58.520 --> 00:24:03.719
transitioning from IC work to management work, maybe not be the first question, but in the

00:24:03.719 --> 00:24:09.000
top three questions is, well, but my skills are going to atrophy, like, that is sort of,

00:24:09.000 --> 00:24:14.760
like, the fear. The fear is that your skills are going to atrophy, and it's, we not, we

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.280
don't do a great job of understanding that, hey, first and foremost, last time I checked,

00:24:18.280 --> 00:24:22.839
like, loops are still loops, right? Like, that hasn't changed much, unless y'all know

00:24:22.839 --> 00:24:27.640
something I don't, but no, that actually, like, this gives you this opportunity to develop

00:24:27.640 --> 00:24:33.319
these incredibly rich skills. Have y'all ever encountered that, where people, like, are,

00:24:33.319 --> 00:24:36.839
like, oh, I don't want to take on this responsibility because I'm going to lose

00:24:36.839 --> 00:24:41.479
something, and have you ever, like, have you provided any feedback to them about what you

00:24:41.479 --> 00:24:48.119
thought about that? I'll take a stab at this. So, I felt this way all the time. I still

00:24:48.119 --> 00:24:55.160
feel that way sometimes, and so, adding to what Hilary said earlier, part of transitioning to

00:24:55.160 --> 00:25:00.280
being in a more of a leadership role is trying to redefine what success means. So, for me,

00:25:00.280 --> 00:25:04.520
success is not being the smartest person in the room, or trying to be, like, the best coder,

00:25:04.520 --> 00:25:10.520
trying to write, like, the most compact, like, bit of code possible. I think of it as, like,

00:25:10.520 --> 00:25:15.719
Angela does, like, having been in this role for quite some time, is how can I enable people to

00:25:15.719 --> 00:25:21.880
do their best work, and how can I give them the resources to do it? So, that's sort of been, like,

00:25:21.880 --> 00:25:28.119
a slow transition, but it's, like, okay to be at peace with it after some time. Yeah.

00:25:28.119 --> 00:25:35.239
And I think it's okay to not want to be a manager. You can lead. You can speak at conferences,

00:25:35.239 --> 00:25:41.719
and find the tone of the conversation, and help spearhead the evolution of the discipline without

00:25:41.719 --> 00:25:49.000
having people whose time cards you approve. That's fine. There's the evolution of individual

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:55.959
contribution is not management, but I don't think there's anything that should stop anybody who

00:25:55.959 --> 00:26:03.000
wants to pursue it, who has the opportunity to do so. A door opens, or a window opens,

00:26:04.439 --> 00:26:10.839
but I think if you have any hesitation, it's worthwhile to explore that. It's worthwhile

00:26:10.839 --> 00:26:16.599
to explore whether that hesitation is coming from a place of insecurity, and fear, and imposter

00:26:16.599 --> 00:26:23.000
syndrome. It's okay to wonder if you're going for the management role, because in some circles,

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:27.479
it has more prestige. If you're fearing, if you're cowing away from it, because in our circles, it has

00:26:28.040 --> 00:26:36.040
perhaps less of a prestige, because our identities are so tied to the product of our code.

00:26:36.839 --> 00:26:41.479
So, I think all of those are valid. I don't think there's any wrong way to explore this,

00:26:41.479 --> 00:26:46.520
as long as you have the knowledge that it's perfectly doable, and it's perfectly valid to

00:26:46.520 --> 00:26:51.959
not want to do it either. I love that. So, I'm going to move on to the next question, if that's

00:26:51.959 --> 00:26:59.079
all right. So, we've talked about ICs. We've talked about the transition of ICs to leadership.

00:26:59.880 --> 00:27:04.199
Let's talk about organizations for a second. Data science organizations grow and change.

00:27:04.839 --> 00:27:10.119
In the organization that you've seen grow and change, in an organization you've seen grow and

00:27:10.119 --> 00:27:14.199
change, what is the most important lesson you've learned about what to do, and what is the most

00:27:14.199 --> 00:27:18.760
important thing that you've learned that you should absolutely not do? I'll kick off. The big

00:27:18.760 --> 00:27:25.959
one that I've learned is you don't hire data scientists if you don't have data. It sounds

00:27:25.959 --> 00:27:32.839
goofy, but there are so many times that I've seen people hire data scientists. They're like, oh,

00:27:32.839 --> 00:27:35.560
and we'll build a system, and we'll collect data, and then you'll get to do stuff with it.

00:27:36.680 --> 00:27:43.160
Yeah. Carly? Tracy? What are things you've learned to do or not to do in growing organizations?

00:27:43.160 --> 00:27:48.439
Yeah. So, we're not a data science organization. We have data, though.

00:27:53.719 --> 00:27:57.079
Yeah. I think that's a really interesting question, and I think it also depends

00:27:57.800 --> 00:28:03.719
a little bit on the organization. I mean, for us personally as a non-profit, we went from

00:28:03.719 --> 00:28:11.319
one person to a couple organizations and mergers, and now we're a team of about 10.

00:28:12.920 --> 00:28:22.920
And so, I think one of the things maybe not to do slash to do is to think about where you want to be

00:28:22.920 --> 00:28:29.239
when you're setting up your structures. I think some of the decisions made early on are

00:28:29.959 --> 00:28:36.199
lock you into certain things because they don't envision where you're going. And it's really hard

00:28:36.199 --> 00:28:43.000
to envision that future sometimes at the beginning, but I guess what I say sort of all the time, and

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:48.520
my team laughs at me, is let's take a step back. Forging ahead on this thing, okay, let's take a

00:28:48.520 --> 00:28:54.280
step back. Where is it that we want to go? How can we not overbuild it, but give ourselves when

00:28:54.280 --> 00:28:58.439
we're creating this thing the flexibility for it to be something bigger for it to scale?

00:28:59.800 --> 00:29:06.920
And I think the point is that you'll get it wrong a lot, but only by getting it wrong do you kind

00:29:06.920 --> 00:29:16.520
of learn what to do next time. Anyone else? Yeah. I mean, I think one thing that I've seen

00:29:17.319 --> 00:29:23.719
in the organizations I've been a part of is the importance of adapting as a business grows.

00:29:24.439 --> 00:29:31.000
And so, I think that a couple years ago, I was really into blameless postmortems, and I was,

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:36.199
you know, reading a lot about them and talking about them. And I think that what I really like

00:29:36.199 --> 00:29:42.119
about them is that it sets up this paradigm for very explicit kind of ROI discussions. I mean,

00:29:42.119 --> 00:29:45.880
I think, you know, this is something that obviously managers and leaders think about all

00:29:45.880 --> 00:29:50.520
the time, but I think that there's some really important decisions in data work, especially

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:56.040
about, you know, like, for example, being the full stack data scientist is very appropriate

00:29:56.040 --> 00:30:01.800
for an early stage startup where you need to build scrappy solutions quickly, and, you know,

00:30:01.800 --> 00:30:07.319
you want to be able to function independently. But as you become a more mature organization,

00:30:07.319 --> 00:30:12.920
like, that model sort of becomes less and less feasible. You have, like, more of a higher

00:30:12.920 --> 00:30:17.079
standard for the algorithms you put out, as well as the, you know, front-end experience for the

00:30:17.079 --> 00:30:22.520
clients or the back-end experience. You know, you consider technical debt in a different way.

00:30:23.319 --> 00:30:29.800
And so, I think just, like, having very explicit regroups about, like, okay, here was the tradeoff

00:30:29.800 --> 00:30:35.800
we made for, like, nimbleness versus kind of future-proofing, and, you know, five years later,

00:30:35.800 --> 00:30:40.760
what does that look like? I think that that's something it's, there's this great paper about

00:30:40.760 --> 00:30:45.479
how machine learning is the high-interest credit card of technical debt. I think that's absolutely

00:30:45.479 --> 00:30:51.400
true. And so, and the paper goes and, like, explains exactly why, but in general, machine

00:30:51.400 --> 00:30:56.599
learning systems are very complex. There's a lot of hidden assumptions in them, and the technical

00:30:56.599 --> 00:31:03.000
debt can scale really fast and in invisible ways. And so, I think, yeah, just, like, having these

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:07.800
explicit check-ins about what's appropriate for our org right now is super important.

00:31:10.280 --> 00:31:15.079
Anyone else? Can I say something? Yeah. I think two other things, now that I think about it,

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:22.199
is one is investing in systems that allow your team to work effectively together,

00:31:23.079 --> 00:31:29.160
and that's, like, physical systems, maybe that's project management or communication strategies,

00:31:29.160 --> 00:31:36.280
but also around the values that you share as a team and having a shared sense of what that means,

00:31:36.839 --> 00:31:41.479
and so not just what communication channel you're going to use, but how are you going to communicate

00:31:41.479 --> 00:31:48.280
with each other. And that shared sense makes, I think, all the work a little bit easier and,

00:31:48.280 --> 00:31:53.560
again, is kind of that thing that helps set the stage for scaling. I think, like Hilary was saying,

00:31:53.560 --> 00:31:58.520
knowing when to do that is always a little challenging, but it's usually sooner than you

00:31:58.520 --> 00:32:04.760
think you should, because when you wait, it gets a lot harder. So, it's that point where you, like,

00:32:04.760 --> 00:32:10.439
feel the pain, but not totally catastrophic yet, but even if it's totally catastrophic,

00:32:10.439 --> 00:32:16.760
you still can do it. So, don't hire data scientists without data. I'm actually going to add

00:32:16.760 --> 00:32:21.160
another one that I'm curious what you all think. I think a big mistake I've seen in organizations

00:32:21.160 --> 00:32:28.680
is over-hiring. What I've seen is, basically, data scientists will get hired and there isn't a

00:32:28.680 --> 00:32:33.959
clear success criteria, there isn't a clear thing for them to do, and they're just sort of, like,

00:32:33.959 --> 00:32:39.719
brought into the organization and told, figure stuff out. Have you ever experienced that? And

00:32:39.719 --> 00:32:43.160
how do you, you know, how do you think about that problem and combating it in the organizations

00:32:43.160 --> 00:32:53.479
you're in right now? Yeah, no comment on if I've experienced it before, but I think one thing

00:32:53.479 --> 00:32:59.239
that's really challenging and exciting about this field is that, in general, like, the product

00:32:59.239 --> 00:33:04.760
management of machine learning systems is a new thing. I mean, I imagine, I think Facebook has

00:33:04.760 --> 00:33:10.119
some really excellent kind of technical machine learning PMs, but I think you're kind of not

00:33:10.119 --> 00:33:16.040
alone, but there's not many folks doing this well. And so, especially with kind of smaller orgs, I

00:33:16.040 --> 00:33:23.880
think that the data science can be a black box, you know, I think that's kind of a common thread,

00:33:23.880 --> 00:33:32.920
and so having a mature understanding of machine learning within product management can be very

00:33:32.920 --> 00:33:38.760
difficult. And again, kind of this thing I was alluding to earlier about leadership, I think

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:44.280
that data scientists can be really uniquely positioned to guide machine learning product

00:33:44.280 --> 00:33:51.000
development, and because they understand the problem in a unique way that probably most people

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:57.239
in the org don't understand it. And so, I think that, yes, I have seen teams kind of just pop up,

00:33:57.239 --> 00:34:01.719
and it's like, hey, have fun, and they'll throw a junior PM on the project, and I think that's the

00:34:01.719 --> 00:34:07.079
wrong thing. I actually think you need a pretty senior technical PM, or you need people, data

00:34:07.079 --> 00:34:12.919
scientists who are acting, like, taking on some of the responsibilities of product development,

00:34:12.919 --> 00:34:18.600
and thinking really creatively about, like, what can we realistically solve. So, yeah, that's one

00:34:18.600 --> 00:34:25.000
of the ways that I've seen, like, a failure, and kind of where I think the solution lies.

00:34:27.000 --> 00:34:30.120
All right, if it's okay with everyone, I'll move on to the fourth question.

00:34:30.120 --> 00:34:30.520
Yeah.

00:34:30.520 --> 00:34:35.000
All right. So, again, we've talked about ICs, we've talked about becoming leaders,

00:34:35.000 --> 00:34:39.000
we've talked about organizations, and all of these around growth, and now I'm going to talk

00:34:39.000 --> 00:34:45.560
about responsibilities, right? Our responsibilities as data scientists are significant. As we've seen,

00:34:45.560 --> 00:34:49.959
the ways that data can be used or misused, and I've personally felt the weight of the responsibility

00:34:49.959 --> 00:34:55.879
as a data professional, grow. I think that when I hired my first ML engineer in 1999,

00:34:55.879 --> 00:34:59.879
I don't think that I had a great understanding of the responsibilities that this new world would

00:34:59.879 --> 00:35:05.239
create. When you look forward, what are the principles by which you hope to shape the policies

00:35:05.239 --> 00:35:10.919
and practices of data science to assure that your work is responsible? Angela?

00:35:12.120 --> 00:35:17.479
I'll tie the answer to this question with an addendum to the last one, which is, one of the

00:35:17.479 --> 00:35:23.320
things that I have learned not to do is, when you have established that you have a need, you have

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:31.800
established what the success criterion is, or the criteria are, and you're out and you're recruiting,

00:35:32.600 --> 00:35:38.679
and you're attracting talent, and you have a team, perhaps, at your organization for talent

00:35:38.679 --> 00:35:43.719
acquisition, and they've brought in several resumes, and now I have my resumes, and I'm

00:35:43.719 --> 00:35:49.639
looking at them. The one thing that I would say you shouldn't do is you should not hire the best

00:35:49.639 --> 00:35:55.159
of the people you have at hand, or the best of the people that you've interviewed. I think one of

00:35:55.159 --> 00:36:00.600
the things that we have a little bit is that you interview somebody, they're extremely smart,

00:36:01.719 --> 00:36:06.600
they're personable, and whatever, they would just be a bad fit. That's not a negative. That's not

00:36:06.600 --> 00:36:14.040
something that is a personal failure of them. It's just not a good fit, and so I think going forward,

00:36:14.040 --> 00:36:21.639
part of that is having a better group of people to choose from. Better not in the

00:36:21.639 --> 00:36:27.479
personal qualities, but better as in how they fit, what your goals are, and what the organization

00:36:27.479 --> 00:36:32.520
is going to be, and so that's the answer to the last question. Don't do that, and how it fits to

00:36:32.520 --> 00:36:41.159
this is going forward. I would love to have organizations metabolize the fact that it is

00:36:41.159 --> 00:36:48.600
so important to have people working at your organization, people teaching at your academy,

00:36:49.479 --> 00:36:55.560
who are representative of the world, because one of the things that we learn in data science,

00:36:56.120 --> 00:37:02.439
and one of the things that I'm adamant about, is that data isn't, and Hillary and I have had

00:37:02.439 --> 00:37:09.399
lots of conversations about this, data alone isn't ground truth. Data are artifacts of systems. They're

00:37:09.399 --> 00:37:16.919
breadcrumbs. There's this amazing book, which I'm going to butcher. I think it's All Tomorrows,

00:37:16.919 --> 00:37:24.760
but I'll tweet about it. It is, in essence, paleo artists imagining what animals could look like,

00:37:24.760 --> 00:37:30.360
so I don't know if anybody has ever imagined a T-Rex without the teeth glaring, right? Like,

00:37:30.360 --> 00:37:35.800
every representation that we see has that, and so these folks who are trained as paleo artists,

00:37:35.800 --> 00:37:44.360
who are trained to imagine what flesh and cartilage look like on these extant bones,

00:37:44.360 --> 00:37:50.120
they reimagine what a manatee looks like, and it's landfaring, or they imagine what

00:37:51.800 --> 00:37:58.439
a swan looks like, and it doesn't have a neck the way that we know they do, because these bones

00:37:58.439 --> 00:38:04.360
aren't truth. They're artifacts that we have access to, but they don't tell the whole story,

00:38:04.360 --> 00:38:08.919
and for you to be able to ask better questions, for you to be able to imagine different futures,

00:38:08.919 --> 00:38:17.239
for you to be able to allow for the fact that that data might be only a partial truth,

00:38:17.239 --> 00:38:22.360
you need people in your organization who have experienced that and who know to question that,

00:38:22.360 --> 00:38:27.080
and who know to question that things aren't what you expect them to be. They are what they are,

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:33.879
and our job is to try to build inference models and to try to understand what that data is telling

00:38:33.959 --> 00:38:40.760
us, but I think it's a problem when we use the data as the metric rather than as the channel for

00:38:40.760 --> 00:38:45.879
what it is that we're trying to do, so how I hope that informs the theory and the praxis of the

00:38:45.879 --> 00:38:52.760
discipline is for us to be mindful of the fact that we need lots of perspectives to ask lots of

00:38:52.760 --> 00:38:59.000
different questions so that we get a more well-rounded understanding of what data is telling us.

00:38:59.479 --> 00:39:04.760
That's fantastic. I mean, I'll jump in on that because I actually share an office,

00:39:04.760 --> 00:39:07.399
or one of my offices I share with an actual T-Rex.

00:39:10.439 --> 00:39:15.000
Like back in the day, someone, I don't remember who this was off the top of my head, but

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:21.800
assembled like a stegosaurus skeleton as like a unicorn because they didn't have a mental model

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:28.679
of what it looked like, but the real point is like having good data science teams means having

00:39:28.679 --> 00:39:33.959
very diverse data science teams, people that bring a lot of different ideas together and also

00:39:33.959 --> 00:39:40.439
thinking a lot about how to make your work just broadly reproducible and effective and owning

00:39:40.439 --> 00:39:47.479
your mistakes because we all make mistakes and owning issues that happen with data and then

00:39:47.479 --> 00:39:53.560
going back and talking about things like blameless postmortems. These are all things that are

00:39:53.560 --> 00:39:59.479
valuable, and so last year a handful of us got together and started writing down what we think

00:39:59.479 --> 00:40:05.639
are ethical guidelines to be a good data scientist, so we captured all this in a manifesto. I think

00:40:05.639 --> 00:40:10.919
it's datasciencemanifesto.org. I can't quite remember, but I'll tweet it out, but I try to

00:40:10.919 --> 00:40:17.000
think about all these things every time. I try to assemble a team for a project, and like Angela

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:21.239
says, you don't just grab the best person out of like a list of CVs and just say like you.

00:40:21.959 --> 00:40:24.360
You think more about the team more holistically.

00:40:26.199 --> 00:40:31.399
Tracy? Yeah, I would echo what Karthik said, and we saw that question. I said, Karthik,

00:40:31.399 --> 00:40:36.600
what's the manifesto that you wrote? Because I think it is having something to kind of tie

00:40:36.600 --> 00:40:43.879
back every decision that you make, so you're faced every day with decisions that

00:40:44.760 --> 00:40:50.760
affect people, right? I think that is one of the great things and the terrifying things at the same

00:40:50.760 --> 00:40:57.320
time. What's your process like when you make that decision? What's your foundation? So something

00:40:57.320 --> 00:41:03.239
like this manifesto or your personal values or your company's values, how do you think about

00:41:03.239 --> 00:41:09.879
those things and everything that you do? I think it is interesting as I give talks,

00:41:10.919 --> 00:41:16.919
especially in a public setting, the question we get most often is around the data ethics,

00:41:16.919 --> 00:41:23.239
and almost no one on the panel or anyone speaking has anything to say about it.

00:41:25.159 --> 00:41:33.639
So thinking about what we would say and being more intentional in communicating that

00:41:34.280 --> 00:41:40.840
to the people who use the products or the community at large and engaging them, being

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:48.040
open to engaging them in that conversation as well. Yeah, I think all very excellent points.

00:41:48.040 --> 00:41:52.840
I'll add that there's Cathy O'Neill wrote a book called Weapons of Math Destruction,

00:41:53.719 --> 00:41:59.000
and I think that one of the key takeaways she has is that we should have kind of a data science

00:41:59.000 --> 00:42:05.159
version of a Hippocratic Oath, which is the oath that doctors take, and I think that's a great idea.

00:42:05.159 --> 00:42:10.679
I mean, establishing kind of a community-wide standard of the values that we have, I think,

00:42:10.679 --> 00:42:17.080
is important. Obviously, it doesn't prevent like, you know, not every doctor is necessarily ethical,

00:42:17.080 --> 00:42:21.560
but I think it's a step in the right direction. And then the other quick thing I'll add is that

00:42:21.560 --> 00:42:27.080
frequently as data scientists, kind of to all the points about like diversity and having people

00:42:27.080 --> 00:42:33.000
bring things up, I think that frequently, again, with the black box machine learning thing,

00:42:33.560 --> 00:42:39.800
a lot of times, you can't rely on other parts of the organization necessarily

00:42:39.800 --> 00:42:45.159
understanding the issues. So, taking that responsibility to surface things and explain

00:42:45.159 --> 00:42:51.080
the implications, and yeah, taking ownership of that, I think is really important for data scientists.

00:42:51.639 --> 00:42:58.520
Yeah, I'm just going to, that ownership is critical. Product isn't going to do it.

00:42:58.520 --> 00:43:03.479
Product is trying to shape the future, right? Engineering is trying to build it, you know.

00:43:03.479 --> 00:43:07.560
At the end of the day, we are the ones who have this responsibility, and I would love to see a

00:43:07.560 --> 00:43:12.199
world in which chief data officers, in which all the way from chief data officers to the

00:43:12.199 --> 00:43:17.639
entry-level data scientists, was keenly aware that this was them. They were the bar.

00:43:17.639 --> 00:43:21.639
They were where the buck stops, and I really hope that we're able to continue that.

00:43:22.520 --> 00:43:26.360
So, we're almost running out of time. I think it's time for us to take some questions from

00:43:26.360 --> 00:43:31.800
the audience. Hopefully, are the flying mics going to be deployed? What's the,

00:43:33.080 --> 00:43:36.919
I don't know what the plan is exactly. It's a great bad name. The flying mics.

