are going to see people and hand mics off. All right, over there. Hi, I'm curious what is the

00:43:53.000 --> 00:43:58.919
most effective way you've seen product management and data science work together and actually

00:43:58.919 --> 00:44:03.800
accomplish things? Because there always seems to be a hierarchical shift depending on the project,

00:44:03.800 --> 00:44:08.199
and I don't necessarily know how it fits, especially with your experience.

00:44:09.639 --> 00:44:13.159
Does anyone want to take? I mean, I've got a take, but if y'all have a take, I'd prefer to hear it.

00:44:13.159 --> 00:44:18.840
I mean, I'm very lucky right now in that data science is one of our key competitive advantages

00:44:18.840 --> 00:44:23.399
as Stitch Fix. So, you know, there's obviously other personal styling services out there. So,

00:44:23.399 --> 00:44:27.080
it's kind of like a freebie for me because I'm like, oh yeah, just be a great partner and like

00:44:27.080 --> 00:44:32.840
come up with ideas. But I think, I mean, I'm just sort of repeating myself, but I think

00:44:34.199 --> 00:44:39.159
not assuming that your place is just to crunch numbers and like thinking much more broadly and

00:44:39.159 --> 00:44:43.639
systematically about the problems that you can solve. I think that, I mean, product managers

00:44:43.639 --> 00:44:49.320
want to put good products out there. And so, if you work on solving that problem, then I think

00:44:49.320 --> 00:44:54.760
that they will respond to that or at least that's been my experience. And so, just like coming to

00:44:54.760 --> 00:44:59.560
the table, assuming, again, this takes confidence, it takes personal development, but kind of

00:44:59.560 --> 00:45:05.000
assuming that you're a partner, not someone who's receiving tasks, I think that that can go a long

00:45:05.000 --> 00:45:09.399
way. And then obviously, like actually partnering and helping bring something to life.

00:45:09.959 --> 00:45:15.399
I think that's right. One thing that I'll add very tactically is whatever your planning cycle is,

00:45:15.399 --> 00:45:22.199
product has a roadmap. Make sure data science also has a roadmap. Make sure that that roadmap is

00:45:23.000 --> 00:45:28.199
correlated and complementary to the product roadmap, but not directly tied to it. And then

00:45:28.199 --> 00:45:32.760
make product see the value in that roadmap. Because that allows you to then have very,

00:45:32.760 --> 00:45:37.239
very real talks when product comes down and asks hard questions about the tradeoffs that

00:45:38.199 --> 00:45:42.919
are going to be required. I think that we as data science organizations oftentimes don't do that,

00:45:42.919 --> 00:45:46.040
and I think it's a critical thing to do. Yeah. Totally agree.

00:45:47.479 --> 00:45:53.959
All right. Next question. Hi. We've talked about this a little bit, but I just want to make it

00:45:53.959 --> 00:46:01.320
explicit. What are common ways that data scientists fail? And if you want to answer it in another

00:46:01.320 --> 00:46:07.800
direction, in your own careers, if you've seen data scientists fired or volunteered to leave a

00:46:07.800 --> 00:46:14.040
team or a company, what happened to them? Why did that happen to them? And I don't mean this in a

00:46:14.040 --> 00:46:20.199
morbid way. I just believe that a lot of times we learn about what works by learning about how

00:46:20.199 --> 00:46:28.120
things break. I'm going to answer first, but I want... I've seen data scientists fail by not

00:46:28.120 --> 00:46:33.399
saying no enough, committing to too many things, being unable to provide anything other than a

00:46:33.399 --> 00:46:39.239
cursory analysis, and then not having a competitive value over a replacement level sort of like

00:46:39.239 --> 00:46:47.080
Excel spreadsheet. That, to me, is the big one. I'll add to that. Ways that I have seen data

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:55.479
scientists fail is by assuming that the product manager knows enough to ask the question in the

00:46:55.479 --> 00:47:01.959
best way, not being collaborative and a partner in helping refine the question so that the ultimate

00:47:01.959 --> 00:47:08.760
product is the best version that it could be. And sometimes that means it's a 180 from what was

00:47:08.760 --> 00:47:15.959
originally imagined. I think product managers are very smart and they're very good at product

00:47:15.959 --> 00:47:21.479
management. They're not necessarily really good at understanding what's possible by sciencing on

00:47:21.479 --> 00:47:29.000
data. And that's where you come in as a data scientist, to step in and to say no or to say

00:47:30.120 --> 00:47:38.360
yes and what if. I think having those conversations are part and parcel of what

00:47:39.560 --> 00:47:49.239
you get paid to do. And you're not just somebody in charge with delivering an output. You're

00:47:49.239 --> 00:47:55.719
somebody in charge with the success of a project, of a product, of an organization. So that's the

00:47:55.719 --> 00:48:01.320
number one way that I have seen failure. And to answer your question, what has happened to that,

00:48:01.320 --> 00:48:09.560
so in a previous life I was leading a team for an organization that was not data scientific

00:48:09.560 --> 00:48:15.959
at its core, but they were expanding into data science. And the market took a turn and difficult

00:48:15.959 --> 00:48:23.399
decisions had to be made and the entire data science team got laid off. My boss, me, the people

00:48:23.399 --> 00:48:28.600
that worked for me, all the way down that whole branch just got chopped and the company sort of

00:48:28.600 --> 00:48:34.040
tightened in and focused on what had been their bread and butter. And this is one thing about this

00:48:34.040 --> 00:48:42.040
community that is remarkable. Within six months everybody had a fantastic job. Not a backup job,

00:48:42.040 --> 00:48:48.120
not a I got to do anything out of desperation because I got bills, but really great jobs that

00:48:48.120 --> 00:48:55.000
were sourced through the community because they knew people who knew of opportunities and

00:48:55.000 --> 00:49:02.040
who knew of good opportunities. And so I think that's part of why we're all here. It's to learn

00:49:02.040 --> 00:49:07.959
how to use our studio and to become kick-ass at it, but to make connections and to elevate the field.

00:49:08.840 --> 00:49:16.360
I'll add that one way that I've seen failure in data science is like caring more about the

00:49:16.360 --> 00:49:22.360
statistical method or the fancy model, caring more about that than about like solving a problem for

00:49:22.360 --> 00:49:29.879
the business. So I've seen a lot of people building some sort of fancy machine learning thing that

00:49:29.879 --> 00:49:36.679
essentially was like a cool intellectual project, but wasn't actually the person wasn't really tied

00:49:36.679 --> 00:49:42.439
in or thinking about what the product needed and like what what the customers of the product

00:49:42.439 --> 00:49:47.239
needed, what the what the fundamental problem was that you were solving. And I think that's

00:49:47.239 --> 00:49:53.719
something that is the impulse within the community. We like to get together and talk about fancy

00:49:53.719 --> 00:50:01.159
algorithms and fancy you know data sources and whatever, but usually like many data science

00:50:01.159 --> 00:50:06.919
problems can be solved with a pretty simple model. And so kind of like letting go of the

00:50:06.919 --> 00:50:14.120
ego around that and really thinking instead about like you'll you will have more impact if you think

00:50:14.120 --> 00:50:19.159
a lot more about the product that you're working on and a lot less about like kind of these marginal

00:50:19.159 --> 00:50:29.719
gains by using slightly different algorithms. All right, we have time. I guess this is a stupid

00:50:29.719 --> 00:50:33.000
thing because there's a comment rather than a question. I apologize. We only do questions.

00:50:33.719 --> 00:50:38.360
No, no, no. Well, let me paraphrase something then. There's a really famous quote about politicians

00:50:38.360 --> 00:50:43.639
that anyone who grows up really, really, really, really wanting to be a politician should never

00:50:43.639 --> 00:50:49.800
be allowed to be one. And I think it's the same for managers. So Angela, you're okay,

00:50:49.800 --> 00:50:54.120
because if you don't want to be a manager, that's probably fine. You're in a good position.

