person that I know. So just being aware of burnout and doing things like Eduardo does,

00:51:56.280 --> 00:52:02.600
I meditate, I do all kinds of things like him, just to like stay on the edge of burnout or

00:52:02.600 --> 00:52:08.360
push myself back from burnout. But one thing you can do as a manager is actually be aware of this.

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:13.639
If you've already experienced this, I can spot this in people pretty easily. So then I try to

00:52:13.639 --> 00:52:17.959
enable them to like step back and then refocus and things like that.

00:52:18.679 --> 00:52:23.399
And sometimes you're in an organization that isn't as respectful of people's mental health

00:52:23.399 --> 00:52:28.120
because of the culture and everything. And if you find yourself in that role and it's incumbent upon

00:52:28.120 --> 00:52:33.879
you to change that, you can make a monetary argument. You can say that if people burn out,

00:52:33.879 --> 00:52:39.239
they're going to leave and the cost to replace them is too much. You can say that them being

00:52:39.239 --> 00:52:42.919
burned out means they're making suboptimal decisions or they're making bad decisions

00:52:42.919 --> 00:52:47.879
and they're harming the product. I mean, there are ways to articulate this so that you can do

00:52:47.879 --> 00:52:53.399
your job of watching out for the people on your team to make sure that they don't have to raise

00:52:53.399 --> 00:52:59.000
their hand once they're past their point of no return. I think I said it in my talk earlier,

00:52:59.560 --> 00:53:06.760
if folks have not read this, Chaos Monkeys, the story of how Netflix has their systems

00:53:06.760 --> 00:53:11.560
architected so that certain systems will go offline on purpose and randomly to ensure that

00:53:11.560 --> 00:53:17.479
there's resilience built in. Maternity leave, vacation, holidays are people chaos monkeys.

00:53:18.199 --> 00:53:22.520
And you have to ensure that your team can survive if somebody has an emergency, if somebody

00:53:23.320 --> 00:53:26.600
gets a scheduled vacation that they're going to go anyway and then something

00:53:27.320 --> 00:53:32.919
poops out. I mean, those are important things to build resiliency on the team and there is a

00:53:32.919 --> 00:53:38.360
business rationale for them. So if you think that you working yourself to death is in the benefit

00:53:38.360 --> 00:53:45.080
of the business, you've got it backwards. And I have no stomach for anybody who brings themselves

00:53:45.080 --> 00:53:50.040
to the point of burnout because they think that's what's expected of them in my team. It's not.

